99
00:05:01,542 --> 00:05:01,782
months.

100
00:05:03,503 --> 00:05:06,404
And I quickly learned that, wow, oh, here's

101
00:05:06,584 --> 00:05:07,664
me at the time, by the way.

102
00:05:09,297 --> 00:05:14,201
I quickly learned that the thing about fame, it wasn't going to work that way. We were

103
00:05:14,661 --> 00:05:19,024
forbidden to tell people that we had created these games. The stance was that it was a

104
00:05:19,084 --> 00:05:25,949
corporate creation. So my good friend Dave Toyer released Tempest. It sold 30,000 units

105
00:05:26,109 --> 00:05:30,432
all across North America and he couldn't tell us all that he created that game basically

106
00:05:30,472 --> 00:05:35,216
by himself. Now the consolation you got for this was that you could put your initials

107
00:05:35,416 --> 00:05:36,277
in the high score table.

108
00:05:37,136 --> 00:05:40,478
And so you can see the creators of Centipede here, Don Bailey

109
00:05:40,498 --> 00:05:42,119
and Ed Logg, and their initials there.

110
00:05:42,219 --> 00:05:42,820
That's the fame.

111
00:05:44,401 --> 00:05:46,862
And then for the fortune, well, turns out

112
00:05:46,882 --> 00:05:49,824
the economics of the arcade business weren't that great.

113
00:05:50,024 --> 00:05:53,287
So we made the game, but we didn't get those quarters.

114
00:05:53,347 --> 00:05:55,228
What we did was we'd add a couple hundred dollars in

115
00:05:55,268 --> 00:05:58,310
