00:06:10,175 --> 00:06:11,915
Those joysticks would break down all the time.

122
00:06:13,316 --> 00:06:16,537
Alternatively, the operator could put the game in a 7-Eleven,

123
00:06:16,657 --> 00:06:18,257
in which case no salaries, no rent,

124
00:06:18,357 --> 00:06:19,477
but only half of the quarters.

125
00:06:19,958 --> 00:06:21,998
And either way, the economics were not great.

126
00:06:22,078 --> 00:06:24,119
The operator needed 10,000 plays at $0.25

127
00:06:24,319 --> 00:06:25,319
to purchase a $2,500 machine.

128
00:06:29,968 --> 00:06:32,230
Except that math assumes there's no overheads at all.

129
00:06:32,330 --> 00:06:34,991
Realistically speaking, the operator needed 20,000 or 30,000

130
00:06:35,792 --> 00:06:37,092
plays to break even.

131
00:06:37,673 --> 00:06:39,654
